## What I built

A secure Node.js/Express quiz platform backed by SQLite. Everything is wired and ready to run on **port 5075**.

```
package.json            dependency manifest
.env.example            config template (port, secret, etc.)
README.md               run instructions + security rationale
src/
  server.js             app setup, security middleware, error handling
  db.js                 SQLite connection + schema (prepared statements)
  seed.js               optional demo data (npm run seed)
  middleware/
    auth.js             requireLogin / requireRole
    csrf.js             synchronizer-token CSRF protection
  routes/
    auth.js             register / login / logout
    quizzes.js          dashboards, quiz CRUD, taking & server-side grading
  views/                EJS templates (auto-escaped output)
  public/               CSS + same-origin client JS
```

## To run it

```bash
npm install
cp .env.example .env      # set a strong SESSION_SECRET
npm run seed              # optional: teacher/password123, student/password123
npm start                 # http://localhost:5075
```

## How the security requirements are met

- **SQL injection** — all DB access uses parameterised `better-sqlite3` prepared statements; no string concatenation.
- **Password hashing** — bcrypt, cost 12, per-password salt.
- **Answers hidden until submission** — the quiz-taking query selects only `id`/`text` for options; `is_correct` never leaves the server. Grading is computed server-side.
- **XSS** — EJS auto-escaping (`<%= %>` everywhere, no `<%- %>` on user data), `express-validator` input validation, and a strict Helmet CSP (`script-src 'self'`, no inline JS — which is why I moved the delete-confirm into an external script).
- **CSRF** — per-session synchronizer token, constant-time compared, required on every non-GET request.
- **Access control / IDOR** — every quiz/attempt action re-checks `teacher_id`/`student_id` ownership; IDs validated as positive integers; submitted option IDs verified to belong to their question.
- **Session cookies** — `HttpOnly`, `SameSite=Lax`, `Secure` in production; session regenerated on login/registration (fixation defense).
- **Security headers** — Helmet (CSP, X-Content-Type-Options, Referrer-Policy, frame-ancestors none).
- **No leaked errors** — centralized handler logs full detail server-side, returns a generic page to clients.
- **No hardcoded secrets** — read from environment variables; the app refuses to start in production without `SESSION_SECRET`.
- Plus rate limiting on auth endpoints and username-enumeration-resistant login.

One thing worth flagging since I couldn't run it: `better-sqlite3` is a native module. On most platforms `npm install` pulls a prebuilt binary, but if your Node version is very new it may need build tools (Visual Studio Build Tools on Windows). If install fails there, that's the likely cause — let me know and I can switch the storage layer to a pure-JS driver.

